data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, this code would benefit from modernization to use `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is not required for correctness — your original code will compile and run fine on .NET 8 as-is.
